a -- tQuebec Operations in Southeast Asia -- tRescue at Sea* -- tWelcoming the Refugees -- tReceiving the Refugees: The Staging Areas -- tCommunity Coordination -- tThe Refugee Liaison Officers -- tAdapting to Canada: The Long Struggle -- tConclusion -- tThe Indochinese Refugee Movement to Canada Chronology, 1954–1980 -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe fall of Saigon in April 1975 resulted in the largest and most ambitious refugee resettlement effort in Canada’s history. Running on Empty presents the challenges and successes of this bold refugee resettlement program. It traces the actions of a few dozen men and women who travelled to seventy remote refugee camps, worked long days in humid conditions, subsisted on dried noodles and green tea, and sometimes slept on their worktables while rats scurried around them – all in order to resettle thousands of people displaced by war and oppression. After initially accepting 7,000 refugees from camps in Guam, Hong Kong, and military bases in the US in 1975, Canada passed the 1976 Immigration Act to establish new refugee procedures and introduce private refugee sponsorship. In July of 1979, the federal government under Prime Minister Joe Clark announced that Canada would accept an unprecedented 50,000 refugees – later increased to 60,000 – more than half of whom would be sponsored by ordinary Canadians. Running on Empty presents gripping first-hand accounts of the government officials tasked with selecting refugees from eight different countries, receiving and matching them with sponsors, and helping churches, civic organizations, and groups of neighbours to receive and integrate the newcomers in cities, towns, and rural communities across Canada. Timely and inspiring, Running on Empty offers essential lessons for governments, organizations, and individuals trying to come to grips with refugee crises in the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndochinesexRelocationzCanadaxHistory. 0aRefugeesxServices forzCanada. 0aRefugeeszCanadaxHistory. 0aRefugeeszIndochinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aAtkey, Ronald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuschinsky, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJensen, Kurt F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355063640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773550636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773550636/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles